T1  - Impact of HIV coinfection on COVID-19 severity and mortality: a multicenter cohort study from Tanzania.

A1  - Osati, Elisha
A1  - Sangeda, Raphael Z.
A1  - Shayo, Grace A.
Y1  - 2025//
N2  - Introduction: Outcomes of SARS-CoV-2 coinfection with HIV have been reported with conflicting results, leaving a grey zone in understanding this coexistence. We investigated the impact of HIV. This study aimed to clarify the conflicting reports on SARS-CoV-2 and HIV co-infection outcomes by investigating HIV's impact on COVID-19 severity and outcomes in Tanzania. Methods: A retrospective cohort study was conducted on 1,387 adult COVID-19 patients admitted to five Tanzanian tertiary hospitals. Complete Case Analysis method was used to address the missing values, where participants with more than 10% of sociodemographic data; and those with missing chest radiological images were excluded from the analysis. Data on demographics, clinical characteristics, HIV status, and outcomes were collected and analysed using various statistical tests, including t-tests, Mann-Whitney, chi-square, and logistic regression. Results: Results showed that 6.3% (87) of patients were HIV-infected, and they were significantly younger (mean age 50 vs. 61 years) but had higher rates of comorbidities like tuberculosis (18% vs. 1.3%) and stroke (4.6% vs. 1.3%). HIV-infected patients also exhibited significantly higher D-dimer levels and mortality rates. Multivariate logistic regression revealed that, after controlling for other factors, HIV co-infection was independently associated with significantly higher odds of abdominal pain [aOR = 27.17 (95% CI: 2.60-283.94), p=0.006], severe COVID-19 (with past TB history) [aOR = 30.77 (95% CI: 2.46-384.5), p=0.008], dyspnoea [aOR = 1.15 (95% CI: 1.02-1.32), p=0.049] and death [aOR = 17.60 (95% CI: 2.18-141.6), p=0.04]. Conclusion: HIV co-infection is an independent risk factor for increased COVID-19 severity and adverse outcomes, including abdominal pain, severe disease with TB history, dyspnoea, and mortality. These findings emphasize the critical need for targeted interventions to protect HIV-positive individuals from severe COVID-19.
