T1  - Hyponatremia as a risk factor of death in patients with community-acquired pneumonia requiring hospitalization.

T2  - Hiponatremia como factor de riesgo de muerte en pacientes internados por neumonia adquirida en la comunidad.
A1  - Barcia, R. E.
A1  - Castiglia, N. I.
A1  - Villaverde, M. E.
A1  - Lanosa, G. A.
A1  - Ujeda Mantello, C. J.
A1  - Aguirre, M.
A1  - Borello, G. J.
A1  - Caisson, A. M.
Y1  - 2006//
N2  - We investigated whether hyponatraemia is a risk factor of death in patients hospitalized with community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) and estimated the relative risk of death by CAP of other risk factors. The design was a prospective multicentre cohort study in 5 centres in Buenos Aires, Argentina, which included adults hospitalized with CAP between 21 March and 21 December 2000. Using stepwise logistic regression, we analysed risk factors that showed a univariate association with mortality, with a level of significance of 0.05. During a 9-month period, 238 patients were admitted with CAP, 150 (63%) males and 88 (36%) females, with mean age of 52.99 (+or-20.35) and 55.06 (+or-20.94) years, respectively. Mortality rate was 10.5% (25/238). By multivariate analysis, the following variables were statistically associated with evolution: cerebrovascular disease (CD) (B: 2.614, p<0.001, RRE: 13.6, IC95%: 3.7-49.6); hyponatraemia at admission or during hospitalization (B: 1.994, p<0.001, RRE: 7.3, IC95%: 2.5-20.8); and elevated urea (B: 0.016, p=0.003, RRE: 1.016, IC95%: 1.005-1.05). We developed a formula to predict mortality by CAP: P (death)=1/1+exp-(-4.03+2.6x1+1.99x2+0.016x3), where x1=CD (yes=1/no=0), x2=hyponatraemia (yes=1/no=0), x3=blood urea (mg/dl). The predictability of mortality was 91.1%. The mortality risk by CAP was statistically higher in patients with CD, hyponatraemia and elevated blood urea.
